## CHUNK 1 — M2 + M3: contract extension + universal injection
*(prompt-only; shippable alone; immediately cuts novelty crash rate. CHECKPOINT after this
chunk before Chunk 2.)*

### Step 1.1 — Ground truth (scout CONFIRMED — verify, don't rediscover)
The contract lives in `evaluation_contract.md`, an **LLM-generated cached artifact** regenerated
from the evaluator on hash change, loaded via `load_eval_context()` (runner.py) and prepended by
`main()` as ONE shared string into every `mutate(...)` call (search_prompt.txt assembly). The
feedback builders do NOT inject it. Confirm this still holds, then work at these two sites only:
the contract-**generation** prompt, and the single `main()` injection point.

### Step 1.2 — Extend the contract VIA ITS GENERATOR (D1)
The contract file regenerates, so never hand-edit it. Instead extend the contract-generation
prompt so the regenerated artifact itself contains the new rules:
- **Serialization constraints — verbatim must-include.** Pass the rules to the generator as
  fixed text it must reproduce EXACTLY (not "mention serialization" — paraphrase drift would
  soften hard rules): (1) custom classes MUST be module-level; classes defined inside functions
  (`<locals>`) can never be pickled; (2) prefer bare sklearn estimators (size introspection
  reads `tree_`/`coef_`-style attributes); (3) save via joblib.dump to model.pkl per the
  interface contract.
- **Data contract:** the existing artifact already has an "input feature contract" section.
  AUDIT whether it is sufficient for a from-scratch candidate (exact `context` keys, data
  paths/format, label shape). If gaps exist, extend the generator prompt to cover them.
- **AUDIT (unchanged):** compare the regenerated contract against real evaluator/runner
  behavior; DRAFT any further proposed sections and STOP for human sign-off. Do not silently add.
- Force a regeneration (hash bump or cache delete) and eyeball the new artifact: verbatim rules
  present, exactly as supplied.

### Step 1.3 — Injection (M3): already structurally done — verify + extend to init-generation
Scout: `main()` already prepends the contract into EVERY operation's prompt via one shared
string. No per-builder wiring needed. Only: (a) confirm all four current operations receive it
(prompt.txt spot-check), and (b) in Chunk 2, route the new init-generation prompt through the
SAME prepend (it is the one operation main()'s loop doesn't cover, since it runs pre-loop).

### Chunk 1 verification
1. Run a short search (`--tries 10`+). Open `tries/try_*/prompt.txt` for one try of EACH
   operation: the extended contract block appears, identical text, in all of them.
2. Eye test on any novelty try produced: generated code defines classes at module level (no
   `<locals>`), or uses bare estimators. If a novelty candidate still pickle-crashes with a
   `<locals>` class, the contract text is not landing or not clear — STOP and report.
3. Report the input-token delta per call (prompt.txt size before/after) so the human sees the
   cost of universal injection.

