## FLAGS — human decisions needed (answer before or during Chunk 2)
- **FLAG-1 Diversity across generated inits.** N independent generation calls may all return the
  same obvious architecture. Default written into 2.2: feed a running "already produced" list
  into each subsequent call. Alternative: one call generating N candidates (cheaper, but one
  failure kills all N, and multi-file extraction is new machinery). Confirm the default or pick.
- **FLAG-2 Try numbering & budget accounting.** Do generated inits occupy try_ids 0..N−1 and do
  their LLM costs count against `--budget`? Recommended: YES to both (they're real dollars and
  real archive entries; `--tries` then means total tries including inits). But SCOUT 2.0 may
  reveal tools assuming try 0 == baseline — decide after seeing that list.
- **FLAG-3 Token cost of universal injection (M3).** The contract lands in EVERY call's input.
  Chunk 1 verification reports the per-call delta; if it's large, options are trimming the
  contract or per-operator inclusion — decide on data.
- **FLAG-4 Skeleton sign-off.** Review the M6 skeleton text by hand before Chunk 2 ships — it's
  the highest-leverage 10 lines in the feature; architecture-free is a judgment call an agent
  shouldn't finalize.
- **FLAG-5 Contract audit options.** Chunk 1's Step 1.2 will come back with proposed extra
  sections — they need your sign-off (that's by design, not agent indecision).

## Build order & models
Chunk R (rename, behavior-neutral) → Chunk 1 → CHECKPOINT (regenerated contract eyeballed +
audit proposals + token delta) → Chunk 2.
Chunk 1 is prompt/text work — any mid-tier model. Chunk 2 touches the init path + selection —
use the stronger coding model; the two review points are 2.3's reuse of `mutate()`'s plumbing
(no second Bedrock call site) and 2.4 routing inits through the existing entry path.

